        phases:1. Tracking and Initialization"Inside the primsAlgo function, I initialize three 
critical components:A boolean vector MST of size $V$, initialized to false. This acts as our visited array, ensuring we don't pick an edge
that leads back to a vertex already included in our growing spanning tree (preventing cycles).A custom tracking integer ans, which keeps a
running total of the MST's minimum weight.A priority_queue structured as a min-heap. It stores pairs in the format pair<weight, vertex>.
Because C++ pairs compare by their first element by default, storing the weight first ensures that the heap always pops the absolute cheapest edge available.

"2. Starting the Loop"We kick off the process by pushing a dummy pair (0, src) into the priority queue, treating our source node as if it costs nothing to reach.
The main loop runs as long as the priority queue isn't empty."3. The Processing & Relaxation Phase"In every iteration of the loop:We extract the 
top element from the min-heap, which gives us the current lowest-weight vertex (u) and its incoming edge weight (wt).We instantly check if !MST[u].
This step is crucial because the priority queue might contain multiple old, heavier paths to u. If MST[u] is already true, we skip it.
If it hasn't been included yet, we officially mark MST[u] = true and add its edge weight to our running ans.Finally, we iterate through all of u's
immediate neighbors. For every adjacent vertex v with a connection weight currWt, we blindly push make_pair(currWt, v) into our min-heap.
The min-heap will naturally sort and bubble the absolute best paths to the top for subsequent iterations.

